<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900502-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>900502-0063.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Day-Care Operator   Pleads Guilty to Fraud   In Communications   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>05/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T ITT WU</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   CHICAGO -- A former day-care center operator pleadedguilty in U.S. District Court here to defraudingtelecommunications companies out of nearly $600,000 as thehead of a nationwide computer-hacking ring.   Leslie Lynne Doucette, 36 years old, working with 152alleged co-schemers, fraudulently obtained 481 telephonecredit-card codes, according to the plea agreement, and thenpublished them in voice-mail systems that were accessed byother hackers. The scheme was discovered when a suburbanChicago real-estate brokerage complained that its voice-mailsystem had been invaded by the hackers, who had changed thesystem's passwords.</LP><TEXT>   Federal prosecutors charged Ms. Doucette last year in thescheme, which according to the indictment resulted in a lossof $1.6 million of telephone and computer services from thecommunications concerns, including American Telephone andamp;Telegraph Co., ITT Corp., and Western Union Corp.   The one count to which Ms. Doucette eventually pleadedguilty carries a maximum sentence of ten years in prison, anda $1 million fine.</TEXT></DOC>